{"title_page": "2000 Reform Party presidential primaries", "text_new": "{{Lead rewrite|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name = 2000 Reform Party presidential primaries\n| country = United States\n| type = presidential\n| ongoing = no\n| previous_election = 1996 Reform Party presidential primaries\n| previous_year = 1996\n| next_election = 2004 Reform Party presidential primaries\n| next_year = 2004\n| election_date = 2000\n\n<!--        Pat Buchanan           -->| image1 = [[File:Pat Buchanan (cropped).jpg|x200px]]\n| nominee1 = '''[[Pat Buchanan]]'''\n| colour1 = 00aad4\n| home_state1 = [[Virginia]]\n| states_carried1 = '''47 + D.C.'''\n| popular_vote1 = '''49,529'''\n| percentage1 = '''63.44%'''\n\n<!--      John Hagelin          -->| image2 = [[File:John S. Hagelin (cropped).jpg|x200px]]\n| nominee2 = [[John Hagelin]]\n| colour2 = ff9955\n| home_state2 = [[Iowa]]\n| states_carried2 = 3\n| popular_vote2 = 28,539\n| percentage2 = 36.56%\n| map_image = 2000ReformMailInBallotResults.svg\n| map_size = 350px\n| map_caption = '''First place by first-instance vote'''\n\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-2}}\n{{legend|#00aad4|Pat Buchanan (47 + D.C.) |border=0}} \n{{Col-2}}\n{{legend|#ff9955|John Hagelin (3) |border=0}}\n{{Col-end}}\n}}\n\nFollowing [[Ross Perot]]'s impressive showing during the 1996 presidential election, the [[Reform Party of the United States of America]] became the country's largest third party. The party's 2000 presidential candidate would be entitled to $12.5 million in matching funds. Several high-profile candidates vied for the nomination, including [[Donald Trump]], [[Pat Buchanan]], and physicist [[John Hagelin]]. For a brief time, Congressman [[John B. Anderson]] and Congressman [[Ron Paul]] were considered potential candidates, but both ultimately declined to seek the nomination.\n\nThe party's 2000 candidates received a great deal of media attention, particularly after a dispute at the party's national convention in [[Long Beach, California]] led to a schism and the formation of a rebel faction. Supporters of physicist [[John Hagelin]] refused to accept Pat Buchanan as the party's chairman, and staged a walk-out, which was broadcast live on television.\n\nUltimately, a court decided Buchanan was the party's nominee, however, the drama surrounding the convention is often credited with leading to the downfall of the Reform Party.\n\n==The campaign==\n\n===Buchanan enters race===\n\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Buchanan 2000 ad.jpg|thumb|left|A Television commercial for Reform Party candidate Pat Buchanan]]  -->During the 1992 Republican Presidential Primaries, television commentator [[Pat Buchanan]] fared extremely well and received 22.96% of the total vote. During his 1996 bid, Buchanan spent a brief time as the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] front-runner; his campaign carried four states, including New Hampshire, Alaska, Missouri, and Louisiana. Buchanan re-entered the presidential race in 2000, hoping to be the primary \"Stop Bush\" candidate. He was, however, viewed much less favorably by his fellow Republicans, and he struggled to place fifth during an Iowa [[Straw Poll]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.politics1.com/buchanan2k.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-03-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715102518/http://www.politics1.com/buchanan2k.htm |archive-date=2011-07-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nReform Party member [[William von Raab]] launched a \"Draft Buchanan\" movement, and in October 1999 Buchanan announced his departure from the Republican Party, disparaging them (along with the Democrats) as a \"[[beltway]] party.\" He announced that he would seek the presidential nomination of the Reform Party, and immediately sought to align himself with the \"[[Russ Verney]] faction\" of the party. Some in the Reform Party voiced concerns that Buchanan, ardently [[pro-life]] and anti-[[gay rights]], would inadvertently move the party too far to the right. During a meeting with Reform Party leadership at [[Pat Choate]]'s [[Washington, D.C.]] home, Buchanan assured the party elite that his campaign would not address social issues, instead focusing on economic policy.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Perot Legacy: A New Political Path|first=Pat |last=Benjamin| publisher=iUniverse, Inc. US|year=2007|isbn=978-0-595-70214-5}}</ref>\n\nAt the time Buchanan entered the race, the Reform Party was engulfed in a feud between the supporters of Ross Perot and newly elected [[Minnesota Governor]] [[Jesse Ventura]], who, as the Reform Party's highest elected official, was rumored to be considering a presidential bid on the party ticket in 2004. Buchanan's campaign immediately aligned itself with diverse factions within the party, including [[Russ Verney]] and [[Marxist]] [[Lenora Fulani]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.socialism.com/drupal-6.8/?q=node/1167 | title=Freedom Socialist Party - Revolutionary feminism in action}}</ref>\n\nOn November 12, 1999 Fulani formally endorsed Buchanan, saying: \"We are going to integrate that peasant army of his.  We are going to bring black folks, Latino folks, gay folks and liberal folks into that army...I'm going to take Pat Buchanan to 125th Street in Harlem.  We are going to have lunch at Sylvia's.  I am going to take him to speak at Reverend Sharpton's National Action Network.\" <ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.gwu.edu/~action/buchpho.html | title=Buchanan Photos}}</ref> Fulani became Buchanan's campaign co-chair.\n\nAt the same time, the Buchanan campaign began to gain support among [[white nationalism|white nationalists]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.newcomm.org/reports/party.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-03-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727120711/http://www.newcomm.org/reports/party.pdf |archive-date=2011-07-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.splcenter.org/get-informed/intelligence-report/browse-all-issues/2002/fall/reforming-right?page=0,1 |title = Patrick Buchanan's Reform Party Begins to Unravel}}</ref> He won the endorsement of former [[Ku Klux Klan]] leader [[David Duke]], who quit the Republican Party and joined the Reform Party to aid in Buchanan's campaign.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.wsws.org/articles/2000/feb2000/ref-f17.shtml |title = Reform Party in US lines up behind ultra-rightist Patrick Buchanan}}</ref> Almost all white nationalists left the Reform Party following the campaign; in 2004 the party nominated [[Lebanon|Lebanese]]-American [[Ralph Nader]] as its presidential candidate.\n\n===Trump enters race===\nSupporters of the [[Jesse Ventura]] faction began encouraging [[Donald Trump]] to enter the race, likely as a placeholder for Ventura, who said he would not consider a presidential bid until after his term as governor ended. On October 25, 1999, Trump joined the Reform Party.<ref>{{cite web|title= Trump officially joins Reform Party |date= 1999-10-25 |website= [[CNN]] |accessdate= 2015-08-25 |url= http://www.cnn.com/ALLPOLITICS/stories/1999/10/25/trump.cnn/index.html |quote= Trump has not yet formally declared he would seek the Reform Party nomination, but he announced Sunday he was quitting the Republican Party}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.albionmonitor.com/9910b/copyright/patdonald.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-03-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707103541/http://www.albionmonitor.com/9910b/copyright/patdonald.html |archivedate=2011-07-07 |df= }}</ref> and for a brief time he seemed to be a credible alternative to Buchanan. His pre-campaign gained a great deal of media attention. It seemed{{weasel inline|date=October 2016}} as though the primaries would amount to a showdown between Buchanan and Trump, the latter of whom remained confident he could win not only the primary, but also the [[general election]]. Trump told reporters: \"It's not so much the Reform Party, it's really the fact that I'd want to make that if I ran and spent a lot of money I could actually win, I could beat that Democrat-Republican apparatus.\"<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.twoop.com/people/donald_trump.html | title=Donald Trump Timeline and Biography}}</ref>\n\nOn October 19, 1999, Donald Trump announced he would file to appear on the [[California]] primary ballot.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.thegreenpapers.com/News/19991019-0.html |title = Donald Trump to file for the California Presidential Primary}}</ref> During the California primary, he received 15,311 votes or 37% of the Reform votes cast, giving him the lead in a five-person field. His total was .3% of the entire California primary vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://primary2000.sos.ca.gov/returns/pres/00.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070630084348/http://primary2000.sos.ca.gov/returns/pres/00.htm|archivedate=30 June 2007|title=U.S. President - Statewide Returns |publisher=California Secretary of State}}</ref> Trump ultimately withdrew his candidacy. During an appearance on ''[[The Today Show]]'', he stated: \"The Reform Party is a total mess! You have Buchanan, a right winger, and you have Fulani, a Communist, and they have merged.... I don't know what you have!\"<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.thedailyshow.com/watch/mon-february-14-2000/headlines---men-behaving-bradley | title=Comedy Central Official Site - TV Show Full Episodes & Funny Video Clips}}</ref>\n\n===Schism===\n\nPhysicist [[John Hagelin]] also entered the race for the Reform Party nomination. Hagelin had run for president in both 1992 and 1996 on the [[Natural Law Party]] ticket.\n\nDuring his 2000 campaign, Hagelin appeared on ABC's ''[[Nightline (U.S. news program)|Nightline]]'' (2000)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.hagelin.org/press_articles/10_30_00_nightline.htm |title=Campaign 2000 |publisher=Archive.hagelin.org |date=2000-10-30 |accessdate=2011-01-15}}</ref> and ''[[Politically Incorrect]]'' (2000),<ref name=\"tvguide.com\">http://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/john-hagelin/246263 TV Guide</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://tv.msn.com/tv/episode/politically-incorrect-with-bill-maher/untitled.411/ |title=Politically Incorrect with Bill Maher |publisher=Tv.msn.com |date=2000-08-23 |accessdate=2011-01-15}}</ref> NBC's ''[[Meet the Press]]'' (2000),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/Meet_Third_Party.htm |title=Meet The Press |publisher=Ontheissues.org |date=2000-10-22 |accessdate=2011-01-15}}</ref> CNN's ''[[Larry King Live]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.locatetv.com/tv/larry-king-live/1316271/episode-guide |title=Larry King Live episode list |publisher=Locatetv.com |date=1992-01-08 |accessdate=2011-01-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120324055005/http://www.locatetv.com/tv/larry-king-live/1316271/episode-guide |archive-date=2012-03-24 |url-status=dead }}</ref> PBS's News Hour with Jim Lehrer,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/bb/politics/july-dec00/hagelin_8-30.html |title=PBS transcript of show |publisher=Pbs.org |date= |accessdate=2011-01-15}}</ref> ''[[Inside Politics]]'',  CNBC's ''[[Hardball with Chris Matthews]]'', and C-SPAN's ''[[Washington Journal]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.issues2000.org/Celeb/John_Hagelin_Foreign_Policy.htm |title=On The Issues web site |publisher=Issues2000.org |date= |accessdate=2011-01-15}}</ref>\n\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Hagelin tv.jpg|thumb|right|Dr. [[John Hagelin]] discusses his campaign on television]] -->\nIn July it was announced that Hagelin and Buchanan would be the only two candidates on the primary ballot.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/opinion/e2209.htm|title=Buchanan, Hagelin make party ballot|last=|first=|date=2000-07-02|work=USA Today|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> Supporters of Hagelin later charged the results of the party's open primary, which favored Buchanan by a wide margin, were \"tainted.\" Buchanan countered that [[Russ Verney]] had allowed the Hagelin campaign to mail a \"Stop Buchanan\" pamphlet using official \"Reform Party\" envelopes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20000816040547/http://www.buchanan.org/wn-00-0712-hagelin.html|title=Hagelin Campaign Brochure|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nMuch to the dismay of many Reform Party members, it became clear that the Hagelin campaign intended to merge the Natural Law Party, which was based on the teachings of [[Hindu]] [[guru]] [[Maharishi Mahesh Yogi]] with the secular Reform Party.{{citation needed|date=March 2015}} On August 2, Buchanan's website posted a copy of a proposed resolution to merge the two parties.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080517041946/http://www.buchanan.org/db00-0802c.html|title=NLP-RP Merger Resolution (Proposed)|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe animosity between the two campaigns reached a breaking point at the party's convention in [[Long Beach, California]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/776469/Feud-may-result-in-2-Reform-Party-conventions.html |title = Feud may result in 2 Reform Party conventions|date = 2000-08-10}}</ref> Buchanan supporters blocked Hagelin and his delegates from entering the convention.<ref>https://www.pbs.org/newshour/bb/politics/july-dec00/reform_8-10.html</ref> Hagelin's supporters declared the convention illegitimate, and announced their ''own'' rival convention nearby, where they endorsed John Hagelin as their presidential candidate.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://articles.cnn.com/2000-08-10/politics/reform.convention_1_hagelin-forces-jim-mangia-john-hagelin?_s=PM:ALLPOLITICS | work=CNN | title=Buchanan says he'll win fight for Reform Party nomination | date=2000-08-06 | first=Matt | last=Smit | access-date=2011-03-17 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101113102820/http://articles.cnn.com/2000-08-10/politics/reform.convention_1_hagelin-forces-jim-mangia-john-hagelin?_s=PM:ALLPOLITICS | archive-date=2010-11-13 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nWith two individuals both claiming to be the Reform Party candidate, a court would have to determine who would be permitted to appear on the ballot and receive the $12.5 million in matching funds.\n\n==Results of the Mail-In Primary by State==\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-style=\"background:#00BFFF\"\n|States won by '''[[Pat Buchanan]]'''\n|-style=\"background:#FB9902\"\n|States won by '''[[John Hagelin]]'''\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n|-\n! colspan=1 | \n! align=center colspan=2 | Pat Buchanan\n! align=center colspan=2 | John Hagelin\n! align=center colspan=2 | Margin\n! align=center colspan=2 | State Total\n|-\n! align=center | State\n! align=center data-sort-type=\"number\" | #\n! align=center data-sort-type=\"number\" | %\n! align=center data-sort-type=\"number\" | #\n! align=center data-sort-type=\"number\" | %\n! align=center data-sort-type=\"number\" | #\n! align=center data-sort-type=\"number\" | %\n! style=\"text-align:center; font-size: 60%\" data-sort-type=\"number\" | #\n!\n|-style=\"background:#00BFFF\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | Alabama\n| 222\n| 79.29\n| 58\n| 20.71\n| 164\n| 58.58\n| 280\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | AL\n|-style=\"background:#00BFFF\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | Alaska\n| 549\n| 79.80\n| 139\n| 20.20\n| 410\n| 59.60\n| 688\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | AK\n|-style=\"background:#00BFFF\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | Arizona\n| 1,042\n| 72.77\n| 390\n| 27.23\n| 652\n| 45.54\n| 1,432\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | AZ\n|-style=\"background:#00BFFF\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | Arkansas\n| 347\n| 80.70\n| 83\n| 19.30\n| 264\n| 61.40\n| 430\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | AR\n|-style=\"background:#00BFFF\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | California\n| 8,166\n| 51.95\n| 7,554\n| 48.05\n| 612\n| 3.90\n| 15,720\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | CA\n|-style=\"background:#F