n| 34.30\n| 822\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | SC\n|-style=\"background:#00BFFF\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | South Dakota\n| 69\n| 68.32\n| 32\n| 31.68\n| 37\n| 36.64\n| 101\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | SD\n|-style=\"background:#00BFFF\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | Tennessee\n| 187\n| 76.02\n| 59\n| 23.98\n| 128\n| 52.04\n| 246\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | TN\n|-style=\"background:#00BFFF\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | Texas\n| 1,877\n| 72.70\n| 705\n| 27.30\n| 1,172\n| 45.40\n| 2,582\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | TX\n|-style=\"background:#00BFFF\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | Utah\n| 88\n| 59.86\n| 59\n| 40.14\n| 29\n| 19.72\n| 147\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | UT\n|-style=\"background:#00BFFF\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | Vermont\n| 31\n| 65.96\n| 16\n| 34.04\n| 15\n| 31.92\n| 47\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | VT\n|-style=\"background:#00BFFF\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | Virginia\n| 239\n| 66.76\n| 119\n| 33.24\n| 120\n| 33.52\n| 358\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | VA\n|-style=\"background:#00BFFF\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | Washington\n| 272\n| 68.86\n| 123\n| 31.14\n| 149\n| 37.72\n| 395\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | WA\n|-style=\"background:#00BFFF\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | West Virginia\n| 78\n| 72.22\n| 30\n| 27.78\n| 48\n| 44.44\n| 108\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | WV\n|-style=\"background:#00BFFF\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | Wisconsin\n| 417\n| 71.16\n| 169\n| 28.84\n| 248\n| 42.32\n| 586\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | WI\n|-style=\"background:#00BFFF\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | Wyoming\n| 254\n| 55.46\n| 204\n| 44.54\n| 50\n| 10.92\n| 458\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | WY\n|-\n! TOTALS:\n! 32,145\n! 65.25\n! 17,121\n! 34.75\n! 15,024\n! 30.50\n! 49,266\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | US\n|}\n\n==Post-Convention==\nUltimately, when the [[Federal Elections Commission]] ruled Buchanan was to receive ballot status as the Reform candidate, as well as about $12.6 million in federal campaign funds secured by Perot's showing in the [[1996 United States presidential election|1996 election]], Buchanan won the nomination. In his acceptance speech, Buchanan proposed U.S. withdrawal from the [[United Nations]] and expelling the U.N. from New York, abolishing the [[Internal Revenue Service]], [[United States Department of Education|Department of Education]], [[United States Department of Energy|Department of Energy]], [[Department of Housing and Urban Development]], taxes on inheritance and capital gains, and [[affirmative action]] programs.\n\nAs his running mate, Buchanan chose [[African-American]] activist and retired teacher from [[Los Angeles]], [[Ezola B. Foster]]. Buchanan was supported in this election run by future [[Socialist Party USA]] presidential candidate [[Brian Moore (political activist)|Brian Moore]], who said in 2008 he supported Buchanan in 2000 because \"he was for fair trade over [[free trade]]. He had some [[Progressivism|progressive]] positions that I thought would be helpful to the common man.\"<ref name=\"indy weekly\">{{cite news |date=2008-10-08 |work=[[Independent Weekly]] |title=Q&A with Socialist Party presidential candidate Brian Moore |url=http://www.indyweek.com/gyrobase/Content?oid=oid%3A266409 |access-date=2011-03-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160104184456/http://www.indyweek.com/gyrobase/Content?oid=oid%3A266409 |archive-date=2016-01-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref> On August 19, the [[New York Right to Life Party]], in convention, chose Buchanan as their nominee, with 90% of the districts voting for him.<ref>(2000-08-01) [https://web.archive.org/web/20020820004727/http://ballot-access.org/2000/0901.html#16 Right To Life Party Picks Buchanan], Ballot Access News.</ref>\n\nOn November 2, party founder Ross Perot endorsed Republican [[George W. Bush]] for president.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0011/02/lkl.00.html | work=CNN | title=CNN Transcript}}</ref>\n\nThe Reform Party never recovered from the 2000 fiasco. Many longtime members departed, the party's funds were depleted, and its reputation severely tarnished. On [[Election Day]], Pat Buchanan only received 448,895 votes, thus losing the Reform Party's ballot access in most states. Buchanan returned to the Republican Party in 2001. During the 2004 election cycle, the Reform Party nominated [[Ralph Nader]] in hopes of relinquishing themselves of the \"pro-life\" label Buchanan had bestowed upon them. In 2008, [[Ted Weill]], who had been a critic of Buchanan, was the party's presidential candidate. Donald Trump joined the Democratic Party in 2001, left in 2009 and remained an independent until 2012 when he returned to the Republican Party, seeking that party's [[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|nomination for president]] in the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 presidential election]] and became the 45th President of the United States.\n\n==Candidates==\n<gallery perrow=\"5\">\nFile:Patrickjbuchanan.JPG|[[Television personality]] '''[[Pat Buchanan]]''' of [[Virginia]]<br>([[Pat Buchanan presidential campaign, 2000|Campaign]])\nFile:John S. Hagelin.jpg|Physicist  '''[[John Hagelin]]''' of [[Iowa]]\nFile:Donald Trump announcing latest David Blaine feat 3-alt.jpg|[[Businessperson|Businessman]] '''[[Donald Trump]]''' of [[New York (state)|New York]]<br>([[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2000|Campaign]])<br>''Withdrew Feb. 14th, 2000''\n</gallery>\n\n===Declined to run===\n<gallery perrow=\"5\">\nFile:Jesse Ventura 2000.jpg|Governor '''[[Jesse Ventura]]''' of [[Minnesota]]\nFile:Ron_Paul,_official_Congressional_photo_portrait,_2007.jpg|[[Congressman]] '''[[Ron Paul]]''' of [[Texas]]\nFile:John_Bayard_Anderson.jpg|Former Congressman '''[[John B. Anderson]]''' of [[Illinois]] \nFile:Ross_Perot_in_his_office_Allan_Warren_(cropped).jpg|Billionaire '''[[Ross Perot]]''' of [[Texas]]\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Refo